Nabokov, Isherwood, West, Fitzgerald, Moravia, Percy, Puig—Moses develops a suggestive theory of novels that use literature to investigate the central role that film has acquired in human experience.These novels, because of their fascination with filmmaker and spectator alike, and because they anticipate current views of the questions of cinema, remain a tangible presence within the repertoire of literary modernism. Offering insightful discussions of Laughter in the Dark, Lancelot, Kiss of the Spider Woman, and other film novels, Moses shows the depth of the exchange between literature and cinema and illustrates the extent to which the way we tell stories with words has been affected by the movies. His book will be of wide interest to literary scholars, film historians, and students of cinema and the novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures in literature. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aambitious investigation.  aart forms.  aaudiences.  acinema.  aclose readings.  afilm history.  afilm makers.  afilm novels.  afilm studies.  afilm.  ahollywood.  ahuman perception.  ainsightful discussions.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary modernism.  aliterary scholars.  aliterary text.  aliterary theory.  amovie lovers.  amovie making.  anarrative genre.  aphilosophical center.  aphilosophy.  apsychology.  ascriptwriting.  asemiotics theory.  astorytelling.  atelevision.  atv.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007943440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520341227?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520341227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520